<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / World Stock Markets (America): NAPM data leave Dow subdued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks were mixed yesterday as investors reacted to further evidence of a
resilient economy, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 3.70 up at 3,846.89 after crossing
into positive territory in the final half-hour of the session. The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 closed 0.95 off at 461.74 and the Nasdaq composite lost 3.41 at
760.88. NYSE turnover was 278.4m shares.
A negative tone was established soon after the first session of the new
quarter got under way, with the release of more data suggesting unmanageable
economic acceleration. The National Association of Purchasing Management
said its September index of activity in the manufacturing sector rose to
58.2 per cent from the previous month's 56.2 per cent.
Even more worrying for the inflation-sensitive bond market was that the
prices component of the survey climbed to a six-year high. As a consequence,
the Treasury market backtracked after picking up some ground in the early
going. Those gains were a response to the partial accord reached by US and
Japanese trade negotiators at the weekend.
However, the relief on trade could not offset the anxieties over monetary
policy. For most of the morning, equities closely followed the declines in
bonds, as the day's economic news reinforced suspicions that the Federal
Reserve was about to lift interest rates for the sixth time this year.
During the afternoon the Dow demonstrated a measure of independence and
staged a minor comeback on the strength of two cyclical issues.
Alcoa added Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 85 7/8 , extending a steady climb which
has paralleled with the recent rise in raw material prices. Goodyear Tire
put on Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 34 1/2 following favourable comments by
analysts last week.
Advanced Micro Devices dropped Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 26 5/8 even though
it announced a 41 per cent improvement in third-quarter net income.
Investors sold the stock because the company said its future earnings would
suffer because of pricing pressures.
On the Nasdaq, CareNetwork surged Dollars 13 1/8 to Dollars 24 after Humana
agreed to acquire the Milwaukee-based health maintenance organisation in a
deal valued at Dollars 123m.
Information America jumped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 5 3/4 on news of an
agreement to merge with privately held West Publishing.
Canada
Toronto ended slightly lower after another cautious day of light trading, as
the market begins to absorb a heavy diet of economic news out of the US this
month, including yesterday's strong US NAPM report which put the spotlight
on inflation once again.
The TSE 300 index was finally off 9.47 at 4,344.71 and falls led rises by
418 to 298 after volume of 43.5m shares.
Mexico
A fresh fall of 2.2 per cent on the bolsa yesterday was attributed almost
entirely to investor revaluations of the political situation in Mexico
following weekend revelations that a congressman allegedly ordered last
week's killing of Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, secretary-general of the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party. There is also widespread belief
that Mexican drug cartels are involved in the assassination. The IPC index
closed 60.10 points down at 2,686.01.
</TEXT>
