<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / International Company News: JAL set to reveal heavy
unrealised forex loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan Airlines is poised to disclose a long-suspected unrealised foreign
exchange loss amounting to many billions of yen, the result of a misjudged
currency hedge.
The group, Japan's largest airline, refused to confirm reports that its
unrealised loss stood at Y45bn (Dollars 450m). It said details of its
finances would be published with the interim earnings report on October 28.
A company official did confirm the existence of a 10-year Dollars 3.6bn
forward currency contract, taken out in 1986. JAL began taking out forward
dollar agreements after the 1985 Plaza Accord to curb the dollar, at that
time valued at Y240. According to market reports, unconfirmed by JAL, the
airline contracted to buy dollars at an average rate of Y185, against the
current rate of Y99.58.
JAL is among several large Japanese companies expected to declare heavy
currency losses when they report first-half results at the end of this month
and early in November.
Until now, companies have been able to subsume currency losses in
depreciation and operating costs. However, the finance ministry has demanded
that listed companies declare unrealised profits or losses from forward
currency trading, starting in the current tax year.
JAL needs to raise an average of Dollars 800m a year for buying aircraft,
about 40 per cent of which it finances through forward rate agreements such
as this, with the remainder raised at current exchange rates, said the
official.
The aim of the new disclosure rules, introduced from the end of March, is to
avoid shocks such as the Y165bn foreign exchange loss on unauthorised
dealings at Showa Shell, an oil refiner, in February last year and the
Y152.5bn currency deficit from Kashima Oil, another refiner, in April.
The early indications of JAL's loss have already caused a mild shock,
sending the share price down 1.3 per cent to Y737 in Tokyo yesterday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Japan Airlines.
</CO>
