<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Sainsbury makes second US foray: Purchase of Dollars 325m
stake in Giant Food sets stage for further expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J. Sainsbury, the UK's largest grocery retailer, is strengthening its
presence in the US by taking a Dollars 325m (Pounds 205m) stake in Giant
Food, the Washington DC-based supermarket chain.
The deal is Sainsbury's second foray into the US, after taking control of
the Shaw's supermarket chain in the north-eastern US in 1987. It gives the
UK retailer a strong position on the eastern seaboard, and a trading
presence in seven of the 10 wealthiest US states.
Giant, the 15th-largest US food retailer, has 107 stores in the Washington
DC metropolitan area, including surrounding counties in Maryland and
Virginia, and 42 in or around Baltimore, Maryland.
It dominates these local markets - with 44 per cent of the Washington DC
grocery market - and made a pre-tax profit of Dollars 151.8m last year on
sales of Dollars 3.57bn.
Sainsbury is acquiring 9.5m non-voting 'A' shares, giving it 16 per cent of
Giant's equity, and 125,000 'AL' voting shares. It will have 50 per cent of
voting rights and the right to elect three of Giant's seven board directors.
The total consideration is Dollars 325m in cash, funded from borrowings and
cash resources. The shares are being acquired from family members of the
late Mr Jac Lehrman, co-founder of Giant.
The remaining 50 per cent of voting shares are owned by the other co-founder
and chairman, Mr Israel Cohen, 82. Mr Cohen has no children involved in the
business, but Sainsbury would not comment on whether it had first refusal on
Mr Cohen's shares in the event of his death or a decision to sell.
'This is very much a first step,' said Mr David Sainsbury, chairman. 'We
will see how things develop. We regard the North American market as one of
the major areas of growth for the group in the future'.
Mr Cohen welcomed the deal, saying he looked forward to a 'productive
relationship'. Mr Sainsbury said he had long admired Giant, founded in 1935,
which had a very similar trading philosophy emphasising customer service and
value for money. The company's non-voting shares are traded on the American
Stock Exchange.
Giant plans to expand into the surrounding states of Delaware, Pennsylvania
and New Jersey, where it has identified 36 possible locations. It expects to
open at least six stores annually.
Mr Sainsbury said this would take it into states where Shaw's was also
planning to expand. He added there was much scope for joint buying between
the chains and Sainsbury in the UK, and for exchange of expertise in areas
such as distribution and systems.
After a slow start, Sainsbury has more than doubled operating profits in
Shaw's over the past seven years, through centralising distribution,
introducing 'value-added' services such as pharmacies, and increasing the
level of higher-margin own- label products to 25 per cent - compared with a
14 per cent average for US food retailers.
Mr Sainsbury said there was scope for similar initiatives at Giant, but
analysts warned that Sainsbury did not have overall control and would have
to treat the US chain's existing management with sensitivity.
Sainsbury is paying almost 22 times consensus prospective earnings of
Dollars 1.55 per share, a small premium to the US grocery retailing sector
which analysts suggested was justified by the opportunities provided by the
investment. Sainsbury's shares rose 2p to 402p in a falling market. While Mr
Sainsbury said the group was still examining expansion options in
continental Europe, yesterday's move suggests it sees the US as offering the
most attractive prospects.
Lex, Page 20
Shoprite warning, Page 26
