<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Exchange set to lose role in settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange is likely to lose its lucrative role in equities
settlement when the Crest computerised settlement system is in place.
Yesterday the Bank of England announced that Swift, the international bank
payments messaging system, and a consortium comprising Thomson Financial
Services and Syntegra, a BT subsidiary, were the two finalists in the race
to become the network provider within Crest.
The successful bidder will carry electronic settlement and other messages to
and from Crest and its users. The exchange has withdrawn its own bid.
Following the collapse of the exchange's Taurus project for paperless share
settlement, the Bank of England took responsibility for developing Crest, a
more modest system to speed settlement. The exchange, which currently has
sole responsibility for share settlement, has been seeking a role for itself
since then. Earlier this year the Bank rejected a request from the exchange
to purchase a 30 per cent stake in the Crest holding company.
Had the exchange been successful in its bid to become the network provider,
it could have secured a source of income to replace its current earnings
from securities settlement. In the year to March 31, these were Pounds
55.8m, roughly a quarter of its revenues.
A key factor in the exchange's decision to withdraw its bid is thought to be
the Bank's insistance that it could not rely on the exchange's Sequal
system, which confirms individual share transactions - a vital step in the
settlement process.
Sequal does not have the capacity to give and accept messages from all
international participants in the London market and would have required
significant investment in order to adapt to the needs of Crest.
The exchange said: 'Our conclusion has been that the business case was not
justified.' However it is still interested in becoming the operator of the
Crest system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
