<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Hoverspeed refit to suspend all Channel services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hoverspeed, which operates cross-Channel passenger services, yesterday
announced plans for a refit of its entire hovercraft and catamaran fleet,
leading to the loss of up to 50 out of 410 jobs.
The decision to carry out the simultaneous refurbishment of all three of its
craft will completely shut down its ferry operations in January and close
the Folkestone to Boulogne service for the first three months of the year.
The company said this move was timed to coincide with the quietest period in
the year for ferry operators.
Hoverspeed normally staggers refurbishments to ensure that at least one
craft is in service, but while the entire fleet is out of service the craft
will have a full-scale refit, the company said.
Hoverspeed plans a complete Pounds 2m refurbishment of the interiors of its
two 25-year-old hovercraft, the Princess Anne and the Princess Margaret, as
well as a refit of their mechanical parts. At the same time it will upgrade
its high-speed SeaCat catamaran.
The SeaCat, which normally plies between Folkestone and Boulogne, will
resume operations between Dover and Calais in February. The hovercraft will
return to service at the end of March.
Hoverspeed said most of the redundancies would be on the continental side of
the Channel and that staff would be re-employed when services resume.
The company denied that the refit is related to the start of Channel tunnel
passenger services, but it runs the only service that can match the tunnel
for speed.
The tunnel launched a limited car passenger shuttle service yesterday and
expects to be operating at close to full capacity by next spring. The
British government might not have 'met its commitments' towards the tunnel,
the project's former co-chairman claimed last night.
Hesitations about the building of the high-speed rail link between
Folkestone and London were 'deeply to be deplored', said Mr Andre Benard,
co-chairman of Eurotunnel until earlier this year, contrasting the British
and French approaches.
Speaking at a Chartered Institute of Transport lecture in London, Mr Benard
said that although there was no commitment from the British government to
build the link, 'there was a clear commitment that the railways would
provide all the required capacity.
'In that respect, we have very serious doubts that her majesty's government
has met its commitments.'
Private-sector consortia are bidding to build and run the Pounds 3bn link
but it is unlikely to be in use before the year 2002. The French high-speed
link is already in place and the Belgian one will be in service by 1997.
</TEXT>
