<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / N-plant risks 'can be priced'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors would be able to put a price on nuclear risks if the government
decided to privatise the UK nuclear power industry, say the US financial
advisers to Nuclear Electric, the state-owned utility.
Morgan Stanley, the Wall Street investment firm, says in a report that
experience in countries with privately owned nuclear utilities shows that
investors are sophisticated enough to be able to put a price on nuclear
shares and trade them.
The report says that, in the US, shares of utilities owning nuclear power
stations have performed at least as well as other US utilities over the past
five years.
It points out that investors are more interested in a management's ability
to handle risk than in the risks themselves.
The report concludes that a privatised Nuclear Electric would be compared to
the highly-rated nuclear utilities in the US because of the strong
improvements in performance that the company has been able to achieve
recently.
Morgan Stanley is advising Nuclear Electric during the current government
review of nuclear power. Its team is headed by Mr Francis Maude, a former
junior Treasury minister who lost his Commons seat at the last general
election.
The conclusion of the report runs counter to the view of the UK government
in 1989 when it decided against privatising nuclear power because it
believed that investors would refuse to invest in nuclear shares.
</TEXT>
