<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Companies House plans attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London users of Companies House said yesterday that plans to contract out
its services to the private sector threatened the future availability of
corporate information in the capital.
About 50 users, specialising in company formations and searches, met in
London to question SRU, the private-sector consultants seeking views on
contracting out.
Companies House, the official repository of corporate information in
England, Scotland and Wales, is based in Cardiff and has five regional
offices. It holds the details of nearly 1m companies and last year handled
the incorporation of nearly 100,000 new ones.
A campaign led by the Civil and Public Services Association aims to kill off
the plan announced by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, in
July this year.
Mr Kevin Brown, managing director of Marriots Company Services, said: 'SRU
did not appear to have any idea about the structure of the market. They
simply have not thought the process through.'
He said his company paid Pounds 60,000 a year in fees to Companies House,
and warned that contracting out threatened much higher access fees and the
future of the London retail outlet. 'I think this is simply an ideological
move,' he said.
Mr Graham Cowan, managing director of Access Company Information, said
London users feared that information might only be available in an expensive
wholesale form in future. He said many small businesses were worried that
carrying out daily company searches would be impossible and that in the end
the London service would be scrapped.
Business information companies feared that data might be concentrated in the
hands of between two and four large operators spending Pounds 100,000 a year
for access.
Mr Peter Scott of SRU said it planned to meet many more customers and hear
their views, and that no final decisions had been taken about the future of
Companies House.
A final report to Mr Heseltine is due in late October.
</TEXT>
