<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Walker defendant 'scarcely involved'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Wilfred Aquilina, a former finance director of Brent Walker, the property
and leisure group, had little involvement in the alleged fraudulent boosting
of the company's profits, his counsel told the Old Bailey yesterday.
Mr Roy Amlot QC, in a closing speech on behalf of Mr Aquilina, also
criticised the prosecution for being 'obsessive and oppressive' in the way
it brought its case against Mr Aquilina and Mr George Walker, the former
Brent Walker chairman.
Mr Walker and Mr Aquilina are both accused of falsely inflating the
company's profits by more than Pounds 19m between 1984 and 1989. They both
deny charges of theft, false accounting and conspiring to falsify the Brent
Walker accounts.
The prosecution claims the profit-boosting took place through the Brent
Walker film division. It alleges that bogus film rights sales were booked to
the accounts of both the film subsidiary and Brent Walker, that the
transactions were funded by Brent Walker itself and that they were concealed
by money-laundering through overseas companies and trusts.
Mr Aquilina played only a small part in the events the prosecution claimed
amounted to a fraud, said Mr Amlot. He could not authorise payments of more
than Pounds 50,000 and his name featured only to a limited extent in the
movements of money. 'Mr Aquilina is scarcely involved in the transfers,' he
said.
He had also received no financial benefit from the alleged fraud, Mr Amlot
continued. The trial continues on Thursday when the judge begins his summing
up. The jury is due to retire on Monday October 17.
</TEXT>
