<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Peas fail industry's 'tenderometers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Far fewer peas than usual have passed the 'tenderometer' test for freezing
this year because of the hot dry summer, causing a serious shortage of
frozen vegetables which will push up prices, processors warn.
The pea crop is down by 10 per cent, while broad-bean production has been
halved. Shortages have been worsened by the fact that the unusually hot
weather spread from as far south as Spain up to Scandinavia so that buyers
are fighting for supplies.
The problem began with the cold, wet winter and wet spring, which meant
crops were sown late and failed to develop strong roots, said Mr Arthur
Whitlock of the Frozen Vegetables Association, which represents the UK's
main processors.
The weak plants then suffered stress from the drought, which also forced
them to mature too quickly. For peas, which are measured with a
'tenderometer' for freezing, the normal time limit for harvesting was cut
from four or five hours to as little as two.
'A lot of the crops had to be left because they got too tough,' said Mr
Whitlock.
The problem is also affecting later crops such as broccoli and cauliflower.
The young plants struggled to establish themselves in the dry weather and
now risk being damaged by the first frosts before they are ready for
harvesting.
'All the growers with whom the processors are contracted are unlikely to
meet their targeted tonnages,' said Mr Whitlock. 'I can't recall another
occasion in the last five years when the UK and west Europe have both been
down the pan together.'
</TEXT>
