<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Home price drop 'steepest since 1990'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The biggest monthly fall in house prices for almost four years occurred last
month according to figures published yesterday by Nationwide, the
second-largest building society.
The average price of a home declined by 2.9 per cent to Pounds 53,918 last
month compared with August.
This represented the biggest monthly fall since prices dropped 3.7 per cent
in October 1990, said the society.
Monthly movements in house prices have fluctuated wildly this year as
confidence among buyers has remained fragile.
Prices in July and August rose 1.8 per cent and 0.6 per cent respectively
following a 0.7 per cent decline in June, according to Nationwide.
The underlying movement has generally been flat, said the society, adding:
'House prices now look likely to end the year little changed from 1993,
although experience will vary widely according to local conditions.'
Halifax, Britain's biggest mortgage lender, is expected to confirm this
trend when it publishes its monthly house price index tomorrow. Halifax's
survey is likely to show very little movement in prices between August and
September.
Neither society expects to see much change in a generally subdued housing
market as a result of the rise last month in interest rates of half a
percentage point.
Mr Brian Davis, Nationwide chief executive, said: 'The recent relatively
small rise in interest rates should have no material effect on house sales.
'We continue to expect a renewed strengthening of the market based on still
excellent affordability and the wider economic recovery.'
He added that the decline last month was due partly to 'a correction
following a rise over the previous two months'.
Mr Davis added: 'As we have said consistently, a single month's figures need
to be seen in context. It leaves the overall trend of stability in prices
this year broadly unchanged.'
According to Nationwide, house prices on average rose by 1.4 per cent during
the 12 months to September. Halifax is expected to show a very slight
decline in prices over the same period.
</TEXT>
