<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Row over minimum wage defused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A row over Labour's commitment to a national minimum wage was defused
yesterday when it was agreed that the party's Economic Commission, chaired
by Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, would draw up details of the
policy.
Tension between the unions and the party leadership on employment law was
set aside with the adoption of motions calling for increased rights at work,
while a radical motion calling for the repeal of all Conservative union
legislation seems likely to be rejected on a card vote.
On the minimum wage, the conference backed a motion calling for a target for
the low-paid based on half median male earnings. But officials said the
commission would prepare proposals on the commitment to be approved at a
future conference.
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union and a member of
the Economic Commission, accused the media of 'mischief-making nonsense' in
suggesting there were differences of view between the unions and the
leadership over the minimum wage. He said: 'We seem to be picking over each
word. In the end it is a matter of trust.'
Mr Tony Blair insisted the minimum wage must be introduced 'flexibly and
sensibly' and not 'foolishly'.
Interviewed last night on the BBC's Panorama programme, Mr Blair said: 'If
we do it foolishly, and some countries have done it foolishly, then it could
have an adverse impact. So we will do it sensibly.'
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said Labour would have
to consider ways of phasing in the minimum wage 'step by step'.
Mr Brown denied the party was split over the minimum wage but refused to
accept that Labour should commit itself for the time being to a precise
figure.
However Mr Garfield Davies, general secretary of the Usdaw shopworkers'
union, stressed that a clear formula and a clear figure would have to be
agreed well before the next election. 'We must have a clear figure so the
millions of low-paid workers will be able to see how their wages will be
improved,' he said.
Mr Arthur Scargill, president of the National Union of Mineworkers, received
loud applause from a minority of delegates when he called for the repeal of
all Conservative legislation and attacked Mr Blair for his 'lukewarm'
support for the rail signallers' strike.
The main motion on rights at work called for the right to individual and
collective representation by unions and a legal right to strike.
However Mr Peter Mandelson, a leading party moderniser close to Mr Blair,
said at a fringe meeting that legislation alone will not help unions.
He said: 'They have got to modernise themselves and make themselves more
attractive to potential members. That is the only way they can improve their
standing.'
He also said that last year's one-member, one-vote reform was only the first
step. He added that the important next step was to increase individual
membership among union members.
</TEXT>
