<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: US to be lobbied on aircraft
job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union officials plan to visit the US to try to persuade President Clinton to
help save almost 1,000 aerospace jobs, Roland Rudd writes.
The jobs will be lost at the Raytheon aircraft plants in Broughton near
Chester and Hatfield, Hertfordshire, when work is moved to Arkansas.
The company bought the corporate jets business from British Aerospace a year
ago but has decided to switch production to its US base to save money.
Mr Bill Jordan, president of the AEEU engineering union, said: 'It is my
intention to contact the president to stress to him what a devastating blow
this relocation will be to communities of skilled people in the UK. It is
asset-stripping of the worst kind.'
The closures were raised at the conference yesterday when the government was
urged to intervene to help save the jobs.
Mr Jack Dromey, national secretary of the TGWU general union, referring to
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, asked: 'Where was the
man who promised to intervene before every meal? The silence was deafening.'
Mr John Weakley, an executive council member of the AEEU, said 4,000 workers
depended on Raytheon. 'Closure would be a further hammer blow for areas
already suffering the harsh effects of massive job cuts in the aerospace
sector,'
Union leaders urged Mr Heseltine, to intervene to reverse the 'catastrophic'
closure proposals.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Raytheon Co Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
