<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Leftwingers capture two NEC
seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two leftwingers were unexpectedly elected to Labour's ruling national
executive committee yesterday in a setback to Mr Tony Blair's drive to
modernise the party.
In elections for seven constituency representatives - the first under
one-member-one-vote rules - Mr Dennis Skinner and Ms Diane Abbott were
elected in fifth and last places.
Ms Abbott, the MP for Hackney North, was elected - after failing to win
enough votes for outright election - under a rule requiring two members of
the constituency section to be women.
However, in a demonstration of the left's continuing ability to mobilise
activists' votes, the highest-scoring loser was Mr Ken Livingstone, the
leftwing MP for Brent East.
Mr Skinner, the veteran MP for Bolsover, returns to the national executive a
year after being voted off with Mr Tony Benn, the MP for Chesterfield, at
the low-water mark of leftwing influence.
The results are an embarrassment to the modernising Labour leaders around Mr
Blair, who had hoped that three vacant constituency section places would be
filled by sympathisers.
Mr Jack Straw, MP for Blackburn, and Mr Blair's leadership campaign manager,
was the only modernist candidate elected. Ms Mo Mowlam and Mr Chris Smith,
shadow cabinet supporters of Mr Blair, both scored fewer votes than Ms
Abbott.
Mr Livingstone said the election results were a warning to Mr Blair to
recognise the substantial level of rank-and-file support for leftwing
policies.
Mr Blair's friends said the election would make little difference to the
political balance of the national executive, which remains largely
supportive of the leadership.
They pointed to strong support for two sitting allies of Mr Blair - Mr
Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, and Ms Harriet Harman, shadow Treasury
chief secretary - as evidence of backing for modernisation.
The leftwing tide did not extend to the trade-union section, which elects 12
members to the national executive. Mr Arthur Scargill, the mineworkers'
leader, was cheered during an attack on the leadership, but finished third
from bottom of the poll with fewer than half the votes needed for election.
However, the elections, combined with the re-emergence of the union block
vote in spite of its abolition last year, fuelled fears among modernisers
that the left might regain control of the national executive unless Labour's
constitution is reformed.
The Labour co-ordinating committee, a modernising pressure group, will today
call for a radical review to reduce union influence, extend individual
voting and extend national executive representation to excluded groups such
as councillors.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, topped the constituency
section poll followed by Mr David Blunkett, party chairman.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the former acting leader who left the national
executive after failing to win re-election as deputy leader, topped the poll
for five women's-section representatives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
