<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Battleground of bruised egos
and shortening tempers - Neither the party leader nor the unions are in any
mood to give way
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Years of retreat may have left Labour's union barons diminished figures with
bruised egos, but they remain a force at the party conference and Mr Tony
Blair cannot afford to ignore them.
Mr Bill Morris and Mr John Edmonds, general secretaries of the TGWU and GMB
general unions respectively, have already made clear this week in Blackpool
that the unions are in no mood to sit quietly on the sidelines in the 'new'
Labour party.
They may no longer be able to hold up their block vote cards to show who has
the muscle in making party policy. But they lost little time in pointing out
that this year's rule allowing union delegates to decide how they should
vote does not mean they can do as they like.
As Mr Edmonds, a former moderniser, pointed out, his delegates are mandated
to represent union policy and not their own opinions. This seems unlikely to
change as long as the unions retain a collective voice at the party
conference.
They still account for 70 per cent of the total votes, and unless Labour's
mass membership grows rapidly, they will maintain a dominant position.
Three weeks ago Mr Blair warned in forthright style at a private TUC dinner
that he would not bow to the power of the unions, restore their lost
privileges or govern in their sectional interest.
It is not the kind of language union leaders are used to hearing. Last year
John Smith signed up to their policy agenda without a qualm. Mr Blair does
not intend to do the same.
He has accepted that there must be a commitment to the aspiration of full
employment, to the introduction of a national minimum wage and to laws for
extending employees' rights at work. However he dislikes being pinned down
to the detail at this stage.
Yet this is what Mr Morris and Mr Edmonds appear to want. The GMB leader is
demanding a precise target for full employment while the TGWU general
secretary insists on a national minimum wage set at half of the median level
of male earnings.
There was a threatening tone in their speeches to the conference yesterday.
Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe, deputy general secretary of the public service union
Unison, did not sound any less threatening.
There is more than an air of unease about their views on Mr Blair. Should he
be concerned about this? The Labour leader is not anti-union, but neither is
he inclined to pander to the egos of union leaders.
As an outspoken champion last year of the one-member-one-vote principle for
choosing Labour parliamentary candidates, he has no time for union special
interests.
He has every reason to believe he is more in touch with rank-and-file
workplace feelings than the union leaders. It is worth remembering that
members of 23 of the 29 unions affiliated to the party voted to elect him
leader in defiance of many union leaders.
Mr Edmonds preferred Mrs Margaret Beckett, the former deputy leader of the
party, but 56 per cent of his members voted for Mr Blair. The left-leaning
TGWU union executive urged its members to support Mrs Beckett, but Mr Blair
secured 44 per cent of their vote while only a third backed her.
In Unison, 53.5 per cent voted for Mr Blair. 'Those amazing results raise
the serious question of who the union leaders really believe they speak
for,' reflected one official. However in the conference yesterday they still
claimed to be speaking for what they called 'our people'.
Union leaders believe they are not a liability in the 'new' Labour party,
and that recent public sympathy for the striking signal workers showed how
times have changed. Some argue that Mr Blair should not turn the unions'
link with the party into a problem.
One senior union official said: 'If you keep gnawing at the union link, it
just reminds people that it exists. Blair should recognise it is a political
reality and move on.'
But most union leaders recognise they have no real alternative but to rally
behind Mr Blair. Even the most intransigent recognise that only he can
deliver a Labour victory at the next general election and possibly save them
from oblivion.
</TEXT>
<XX>
