<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Blunkett calls for delegates
to unite on social and economic policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Blunkett, the party chairman and shadow health secretary, called on
delegates to unite behind policies designed to achieve social justice and
economic efficiency, Ivor Owen writes.
The message sent out by the conference, he said, should confirm that Labour
under the leadership of Mr Tony Blair was 'in tune with the British people'.
Mr Blunkett looked forward to full employment and a national minimum wage
'going hand-in-hand together'. He said: 'Equity and the narrowing of the gap
between rich and poor must be our watchword.'
He also sought to reassure delegates who fear the conference's policymaking
role is being undermined. He welcomed Mr Blair's pledge to follow the
example of John Smith in providing an 'inclusive, open style' of leadership.
Mr Blunkett said this should ensure that 'all of us have a part to play' in
building the foundations for victory at the next general election. The
party's vision needed to embrace the aspirations of the middle classes and
those whose only hope for the future was the return of a Labour government.
Putting social justice and economic efficiency into action should result in
decent jobs and decent wages.
Mr Blunkett condemned the redistribution of wealth by Conservative
chancellors, which he said had been against those who could least afford it
and in favour of those making the most even when they did not deserve to do
so.
</TEXT>
