<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / World Trade News: US declines to use Super 301 weapon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US yesterday unilaterally disarmed itself of its most feared and
controversial trade expansion weapon: Super 301.
The provision of US law once required the US trade representative to name
'unfair' trading nations, list their most egregious trade practices, and,
using the threat of sanctions, negotiate them out of existence.
Apparently, Mr Mickey Kantor, the current representative, became convinced
that further unilateral action would be counterproductive. This is
particularly true since the broad 'framework' approach with Japan - the real
target of Super 301 - had finally yielded market openings in insurance,
government procurement and flat glass, announced on Saturday.
The law expired in 1990, but Mr Kantor resurrected his own milder version
last March. To reduce the stigma associated with Super 301, he said he would
list trade practices instead of unfair trading countries. Yesterday he
declined to list even those, saying they were already being negotiated in
other forums. He made clear that 'the single most important component' of US
trade strategy was the successful implemention of the Uruguay Round.
Mr Kantor did list a number of practices which he said could in the future
'warrant identification as priority foreign country practices'.
These include the EU Utilities Directive, under which the US has already
levied sanctions in response to the preference given EU suppliers in
government procurement projects of telecommunications products and
equipment.
The Super 301 law has been controversial since its introduction in 1988
trade legislation. US trading partners said it poisoned the environment for
multilateral negotiations under way in the Uruguay Round.
A study published last month by the prestigious Institute for International
Economics said the use of US unilateral trade weapons had been 'neither as
powerful a market-opening crowbar as its supporters assert nor the
unmitigated disaster for the global trading system that critics feared'.
It found that 'aggressive unilateralism' did not typically lead to trade
wars, as had been feared, nor to discrimination against third country
exporters. But it expected that Super 301 would be less effective in the
future.
President Bill Clinton promised to revive Super 301 during his election
campaign. Mr Kantor moved to institute his own version of the law when
US-Japan trade talked failed in March. This headed off introduction of a
tougher version in Congress.
As an alternative, the IIE report recommended 'aggressive multilateralism' -
making use of the dispute settlement provisions of the new World Trade
Organisation (which will come into being next year) to enforce global trade
rules. This is clearly what the administration intends, except in the case
of trade barriers not covered by the new rules.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
