<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Shirtless and in shanties, Brazil votes in fair order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday was just another day in Brazil, with a power cut in the capital
Braslia, shoot-outs in Rio de Janeiro and fraud allegations in the country's
impoverished north-east.
It was also the day when Brazil held its biggest set of elections in 40
years and, despite these and other problems, electoral authorities agreed
voting was fair and more orderly than expected.
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso - the former finance minister who, exit polls
suggested, will be Brazil's next president - said the elections had been
more 'ethical' and the campaign less radical than previous ones. After
voting in Sao Paulo, he managed to throw off a pack of journalists and was
thought to be resting outside the city.
Besides choosing a new president, Brazil's 95m voters were electing state
governors, two thirds of the federal Senate, all the House of
Representatives, and all state legislators.
Despite the excitement, voting was reported to be orderly throughout the
country, helped by new rules which banned late campaigning at polling
centres. One less effective rule was meant to ban people from voting
shirtless or in swimwear. This prompted complaints from people going to vote
from the beach.
In the north-eastern state of Alagoas, voting was delayed in four districts
following allegations of electoral fraud. In the southern city of Curitiba,
one man seemed to be taking politics too seriously when he shot another
voter in the queue.
Mr Cardoso said Brazil's priority was 'an end to social injustice'. Other
presidential hopefuls have pledged to bridge the country's huge divide
between rich and poor. But none of the 12,000 candidates running for various
offices visited the shantytown near Vila Clara on the outskirts of Sao
Paulo.
It was built in the last five years alongside one of the city's busiest
highways. Its wooden huts are home to more than 50 families who have no
running water or sewers.
Marinalva, a mother of two, said politicians had never helped the community.
Instead, many families fear that local politicians have been waiting until
after the elections before clearing the area.
Cars returning to Sao Paulo from Vila Clara have to travel some distance
before they suddenly encounter a snow-storm of election paper, which
continues until the main Avenue Paulista, as though voters only matter in
the city centre.
</TEXT>
