<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Inquiry ordered into funding of French political party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French Justice Ministry yesterday ordered an official investigation into
the funding of the Republican party, one of the largest groups in the
centre-right government and which is headed by Mr Gerard Longuet, industry
minister.
The announcement is a further blow to Mr Longuet, under pressure to resign
after allegations of irregular payments concerning a villa in Saint Tropez.
It is also a setback for Mr Edouard Balladur, prime minister, who is seeking
support from the Republicans as part of his strategy for next year's
presidential elections.
The decision to open a formal investigation, which has been rumoured for
several days, follows a report by Mr Renaud van Ruymbeke, an investigating
magistrate, which alleged irregularities in the party's funding. In
particular, he has questioned whether its Paris headquarters were acquired
on favourable terms and how it received an estimated FFr28m (Pounds 3.35m)
in cash between 1987 and 1991.
Mr Van Ruymbeke is also leading the investigation into the financing of Mr
Longuet's villa. Mr Balladur said at the weekend the investigation must
pursue its course but Mr Longuet should resign if formally charged. A
decision on whether to lay charges is due at the end of the month.
The Republican party is the largest element in the UDF, junior partner in
the governing coalition, which also comprises the Gaullist RPR party. Mr
Balladur is engaged in an undeclared battle with Mr Jacques Chirac, the RPR
head, to represent the right in next spring's presidential polls.
The opening of the inquiry will further fuel demands for a reform of French
political funding. Mr Philippe Seguin, national assembly president, has
proposed an all-party study of the legislation and criticised Mr Balladur
for his reticence on the issue. Mr Pierre Mehaignerie, justice minister, has
proposed a separation between business and political party financing.
</TEXT>
