<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 94 / Blair to tell party it must press ahead with reform: Left
makes gains on executive as unions take hard line on minimum wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BLACKPOOL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, will respond today to another bout of
infighting with a warning to his party's Blackpool conference that it must
press ahead with its modernisation programme.
His annual conference debut as party leader - previewed by aides as 'bold
and uncompromising' - will follow a renewed attempt yesterday by leaders of
the main trades unions to set the agenda for Labour's economic strategy.
Mr Blair will tell delegates that 'new ideas, new thinking and new Labour'
are essential for the renewal of Britain. Urging party unity for the sake of
winning the next general election, he will add: 'I want you with me in our
task of renewal. I want you with me head and heart.'
During a sometimes irritable start to the week-long conference, Mr John
Edmonds and Mr Bill Morris, leaders respectively of the GMB and the TGWU
general workers unions, led a series of calls for the party to fix its
proposed minimum wage at half male median earnings.
Mr Blair, however, insisted that although the principle of a national
minimum rate for all workers was sacrosanct, the details of its
implementation would be fixed by the party's economic commission. He made
clear that the system would have to be introduced flexibly, with exemptions
for young people, if it were not to have a damaging impact on employment.
The party leadership suffered a setback when the annual poll for the party's
national executive committee saw the election of two leftwing MPs - Ms Diane
Abbott and Mr Dennis Skinner. Mr Blair retains a commanding majority on the
policymaking executive, but two of his strongest supporters - Ms Marjorie
Mowlam and Mr Chris Smith - failed to win places.
In a thinly veiled attack on the economic policies spelt out at the
conference by Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, Mr Edmonds demanded
that Labour should fix a firm target for full employment. He told delegates
that over the next year it must 'mix some concrete in with the rhetoric'.
The decision by the union leaders to flex their political muscle over pay
and employment coincided with signs of renewed disquiet on the left of the
party over Mr Blair's insistence that middle-income earners will not suffer
through the party's tax plans.
Mr John Prescott, the deputy leader, is thought to be concerned that the
present stance might leave the party trapped by a pre-election cut in income
tax rates by the government. In those circumstances, Labour might be forced
to abandon either its pledge not to raise taxes on middle-income earners or
to drop key spending pledges.
Mr Brown used his conference appearance to attack the 'tax privileges' which
he said subsidised 'boardroom privilege'. Reaffirming that a Labour
government would restrict executive share options and tighten up residency
rules for the rich, he said Labour would 'rewrite the tax rules for the
undeserving rich'.
In what may be the most important speech of his political life, Mr Blair
will tell the party that the ditching of traditional policies does not mark
a rejection of its core values.
Marking out the dividing lines between Labour and the Conservatives, he will
set the party's central ambition as the spread of opportunity and social
justice. But his aides insisted he would leave no doubt of his determination
to widen the party's appeal to a suspicious electorate.
Blow to Blair as leftwingers win NEC seats, Page 8
</TEXT>
